Insight and Analysis of Ford's GoBike System in the Bay Area¶

by Jonathan Clamp¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data-set is taken from Ford's GoBike system across a period of the first 10 months of 2019.

(Source) https://s3.amazonaws.com/baywheels-data/index.html

a full 12 months was initally used - which slowed down the execution of code on my machine - 2 months (Nov-19 and Dec-19 were trimmed from the consolidated dataframe.

Creating additional columns regarding the date and time of the renting.¶

As there is no user specific data (e.g. demograhphics such as age, nationality), my analysis will focus on the GoBike system's journey characteristics.

For instance, I am looking to explore if there are peak user days and routes. This could lead to insight for local traffic management or reveal results indicating why GoBike is more or less used during certain days.

I have added 4 additional columns detailing: Two columns detailing the duration each GoBike jounry lasts (duration_min and duration_hour) The month the journey started in (start_time_hour) The hour the journey started and ended (start_time_hour and end_time_hour) The day the journey began (start_time_day)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The consolidated dataframe of 10 months containts 15 columns with 2,171,285 rows of data.

6 additional columns have been added for analytical purposes as previously outlined.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am looking to explore if there are peak user days and routes. This could lead to insight for local traffic management or reveal results indicating why GoBike is more or less used during certain days.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Volume of GoBike's used, start and end stations and trip durations are key areas of the data-set that will illuminate the analysis.

Univariate Exploration¶

Observation 1:¶

Most trips fell between ~3 to ~9 minutes in length. No trips appeared to last less than ~1 minute and at the top end, a small number of trips lasted longer than 50 minutes but not longer than 1 hour (which for the purpose of analysis, 1 hour is the max trip duration used for the scope of the analsysis).

Subscribers make up ~83% of all trips, while one-off customers make up ~17%.

Observation 3:¶

The graph below shows that most trips are done during weekdays which suggests that bike are mostly used for commuting from home to work or vice versa.

To increase our confidence in this assumption, we need to check the trips by hour as well.

Observation 5:¶

The number of trips by month shows that March and July are the peak months for trip, with May being the lowest. Removing the spike in trips during July and applying a hypothetical line of best fit from May to October, highlights a potential upward trend in trips by month.

Further questions that emerge from this analysis are: Did GoBike initiate a marketing campaign at a certain time of the year or is the increase in volume of trips over the course of the year from May onwards (excluding July) organic?

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The results of the analsysis indicate the GoBke system is likely used primarily for commuting during the week. These users tend to be majority subscribers. Weekend use of the GoBike system drops materially. No further transformations in the data were performed.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

One operation was performed to include trips that fell within a 1 hour duration. Few (immaterial) trips fell outside of this boundary and were classified as outliers.

To avoid such trips being shown in the graph, I visualised trips of less than 1 hour.

The variance of trip duration between the start and end stations is now analysed.¶

In [38]:
# this function is to calculate the distance based on the latitude/longitude

# the code was copied form:
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19412462/getting-distance-between-two-points-based-on-latitude-longitude

from math import sin, cos, sqrt, atan2, radians

def distance (lat1,lon1,lat2,lon2):
    R = 6373.0
    
    lat1 = radians(lat1)
    lon1 = radians(lon1)
    lat2 = radians(lat2)
    lon2 = radians(lon2)

    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1

    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon / 2)**2
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))

    distance = R * c
    return np.float64(round(1000*distance)) # return distance in meters

# generating distance column using the defined function
df['distance'] = df.apply(lambda row: distance(row['start_station_latitude'],row['start_station_longitude'],row['end_station_latitude'],row['end_station_longitude']),axis=1)

Observation 5¶

It was anticipated the trip distance may be longer during the weekend and customers use the GpBike system for leisure purposes, unconstrained by factors such as a defined commute route.

The average trip distance is higher during the weekday and marginally lower during the weekend, disproving this assumption.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Peak volume trips are short in duration during weekdays. Users may be using it transit from one mode of transport to another, potentially a metro system.

On the contrary trips are longer during weekends as people roam more freely. The variance between trip distance is broadly in line acorss weekdays and weekends.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The number of trips during weekends are materially lower than during the week.
